{"key":"post-10575931","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10575931</id>\n<content>I can't say plainly enough how much I hate the process of using a spoon to get spawn out of a jar.&amp;nbsp; The spoon cuts many of the grains in half, leaving the uncolonized center of the grains exposed to mold spores.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Instead, I suggest banging the jar against a tire, phone book, or block of wood to break up the individual grains, and then simply pour them out.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Bulk substrates need not be sterile, nor do you need to spawn in sterile conditions.&amp;nbsp; I doubt that was the problem.&amp;nbsp; Either your spawn was contaminated from the get-go, or you damaged the grains when you spooned them out and that's where the contamination got its foothold.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'm sure others will come along and say they've used a spoon before with no problems, but I stand by the above.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10575952</next>\n<prev>10575928</prev>\n<first>10575890</first>\n<last>10587250</last>\n<when>1246032171</when>\n<utime>06/26/09 07:02 PM</utime>\n</post>"}